Ithaca Commons is an excellent example of a functional district. It is distinct from the surrounding area in many ways. Unlike the adjacent roads, the inside of the Commons is pedestrian oriented (and does not allow for cars). This district also features many commercial and food opportunities which draws people in and further distinguishes the Commons from its surrounding residential areas. These commercial activities lead to creation of the Commons’ commercial identity. The clear transition from traditional roads to the Commons’ pedestrian streets helps signal its function as a district. This relates to the HER Process of Environmental Cognition. #envpsy #envpsyw3

#envpsy #envpsyw3 In collegetown, I think this is the area that fosters the most community. There is visual prospect (you can see what's happening before you commit to the space), there is seating (both unmovable benches and movable chairs), there is nature (trees within the space as well as surrounding the area), there is an area that can block wind closet to cascidilla hall, and there is food (CTB as well as tables selling food every once in a while). The only downside is the street traffic and noise of this area; with the construction going on across the street, it is quite noisy and cars have to stop in that area, which increases congestion. This doesnt specifically relate to a HER process but is the application of legibility of environmental cognition.

This past week in class, we talked a lot about an HER Process called Environmental Perception. This process is demonstrated in this photo I took from the top of the Slope --- when met with light, our eyes take in a scene and deliver not only a pretty day, but an entire composite image. Our eyes can interpret what shadows are and why their presence makes sense where they are. Our eyes understand foreground and background, and the concept of depth (which also factors in with relative sizes).

#envpsy #envpsyw3 #envpsyg205

I am from nyc, and when talking about the HER process environmental cognition I realized why I have difficulty solidifying an accurate cognitive map of Ithaca in my mind. 

First of all, nyc is in a grid pattern. This means it is conducive to walking/I walk a lot there. 

In Ithaca, the paths are more winding and suburban esque and the area is more focused on cars, meaning I walk less here. 

Because I walk less in Ithaca than in Manhattan (especially due to the pandemic) it is harder for me to wayfind at school than it is at home. Of course this also has to do with familiarity of both places, however, I have now spent 2 years at Cornell and still have a hard time navigating Ithaca. 

#envpsyw3

#envpsy #envpsyw3 NEIGHBORHOOD DESIGN: An example of a good neighborhood design at Cornell. Sidewalks are an essential component of the urban environment and serve as key corridors for transportation. A lack of sidewalk maintenance makes walking difficult for pedestrians. In this example, Cornell’s campus features numerous stoplights, clean sidewalks, and bike lanes. In addition, the presence of trees and pleasant scenery makes the pedestrian feel closer to nature. These sidewalks also encourage physical activity and exercise.

HER Process: Privacy. This is a picture of the porch at the house I live at. It is a good example of the gradient between private (inside) and public (sidewalk) space and allows us as residents to regulate how much privacy we want. Sometimes, especially when weather permits, we sit outside to do schoolwork or socialize or eat. When we are out on the porch not only do we have additional eyes on the street (HER Process: Defensible Space) but we are also able to interact with aspects of the neighborhood like our neighbors or the mailman (not unlike the principle at play in “Co-Housing,” one of the alternatives to suburbs we discussed in lecture).
With COVID going on as well, this gradient between private and public is even more important since interacting with someone in your home vs outdoors has a much different threat of transmission. I know here where I live there is a very small and specific list of qualified users allowed in the house without masks. On the porch, the list of qualified users (with masks on) is slightly larger.

#envpsy #envpsyw3

#envpsy #envpsyw3 This week, we talked about neighborhood design in relation to obesity. If trends in BMI in the USA continue, by 2050, four out of ten American adults will become obese. One way to prevent this future possibility is to design neighborhoods that facilitate physical activity. Giving more priority to bicycle traffic increases the likelihood that people will engage in physical activity. Creating bicycle lanes makes areas more pedestrian oriented.
